The research involved 2,000 young people participating in youth employability programmes across SA. JOHANNESBURG - A study conducted at the University of Johannesburg has found many employers in South Africa are not meeting young job seekers halfway in dealing with youth unemployment.The research involved 2,000 young people participating in youth employability programmes across South Africa.The study shows some of the main stumbling blocks facing young people trying to access education which includes transport, internet costs, printing and application fees.The research also indicates predominantly black youth are affected by high unemployment.Researcher professor Gina Chowa says there s lack of opportunities being created. We are not creating opportunities for them to get hired on the demand side. The demand side feels that it s not their responsibility to see that youth are hired. (Edited by Shimoney Regter)